==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prink
<hw>Prink</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Prinked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Prinking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably a nasalized form of
<ets>prick</ets>. See <er>Prick</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Prig</er>, <er>Prank</er>.]</ety> <def>To dress or adjust one's self
for show; to prank.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prink
<hw>Prink</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To prank or dress up; to deck
fantastically.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And <xex>prink</xex> their hair with
daisies.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prinker</ent>⟦br⟧
